{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505220"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2421"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2421"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.61,0.05,0.18,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44751"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2421"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29621"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"6490"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44636"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44751"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of cramping left sided abdominal pain. The pain starts in his flank and radiates down into his scrotum. He has never had symptoms like this before. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, his pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His abdomen is soft to palpation. Urinalysis shows blood. Baseline laboratory investigations are shown (Images 1 - 2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntramuscular diclofenac and 200\u00a0\u03bcq fentanyl are given, however the patient continues to report 9/10 pain. His abdominal signs remain unchanged. On CT there is a\u00a05 mm stone at the lower end of the left ureter with mild left hydronephrosis. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most strongly indicates the need for surgical intervention in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The vital signs","The analgesic needs","The abdominal signs","The stone size","The renal function"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of well recognised indications for surgical intervention in the setting of renal colic. These include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFever (suggesting possible urosepsis)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal angle tenderness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersistence of pain despite adequate analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESingle kidney (on CT)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImpaired renal function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStone size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore the most important of the listed options to consider for some form of surgical intervention is the patient\u0027s ongoing \u003Cstrong\u003Eanalgesic needs\u003C/strong\u003E and intractable pain despite analgesia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother consideration is\u003Cstrong\u003E size of the stone\u003C/strong\u003E, with \u0026gt;7 mm generally considered unlikely to pass spontaneously. In this case the stone is 5 mm and should be given the opportunity to pass spontaneously. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal function\u003C/strong\u003E is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of a fever might suggest sepsis, but in this case the patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Evital signs\u003C/strong\u003E are within normal limits. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen present, renal angle tenderness can be variable in severity and suggestive of infection, but in this case there are no \u003Cstrong\u003Eabnormal abdominal signs\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients outside of these categories can generally be managed medically using diclofenac for analgesia, high oral fluid intake, use of alpha-blocker (controversial), and straining urine for spontaneous passage. It is important to know the indications for urgent surgical decompression of the urinary tract with an expedited urological consultation and theatre management.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The assessment of any patient with ureteric colic must include consideration of the need for some form of prompt surgical intervention."],"references":["Sewell J, Katz DJ, Shoshany O, Love C. Urolithiasis \u2013 Ten things every general practitioner should know. Aust Fam Physician. 2017;46(9):648-652. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/september/urolithiasis","Zumstein V, Beschert P, Abt D, Schmid HP, Panne CM, Putora PM. Surgical management of urolithiasis \u2013 a systematic analysis of available guidelines. BMC Urol. 2018;18:25. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5894235/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29621"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2421"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17466"},{"type":"media","id"